WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.520
Hi, my name is Emily Riederer, and today I'm here to talk about how to design packages

00:00:11.520 --> 00:00:13.800
for your organization.

00:00:13.800 --> 00:00:16.600
Think about the last time that you joined a new organization.

00:00:16.600 --> 00:00:20.920
There was so much you needed to learn before you could start contributing.

00:00:20.920 --> 00:00:25.320
Remember the frustration when you couldn't figure out how to access data, the lost hours

00:00:25.320 --> 00:00:29.980
trying to answer the wrong question before you built up your intuition, and the awkwardness

00:00:29.980 --> 00:00:33.820
of figuring out team norms through trial and error.

00:00:33.820 --> 00:00:38.660
When we join a new organization, we must learn these things only once before we can hit the

00:00:38.660 --> 00:00:39.660
ground running.

00:00:39.660 --> 00:00:45.259
However, the off-the-shelves tools that we use can't preserve this context.

00:00:45.259 --> 00:00:48.099
Every day is like their first day at work.

00:00:48.099 --> 00:00:53.380
Unlike open-source packages, internal packages can embrace institutional knowledge more like

00:00:53.380 --> 00:00:56.060
a colleague in two important ways.

00:00:56.060 --> 00:01:01.180
First and foremost, they can aim to solve far more domain-specific and concrete problems

00:01:01.180 --> 00:01:02.860
than open-source packages.

00:01:02.860 --> 00:01:08.180
Second, although narrower is the scope of the defined problem, their insight into our

00:01:08.180 --> 00:01:13.739
organization allows them to be more holistic in the solutions they propose by internalizing

00:01:13.739 --> 00:01:18.620
more steps of the necessary workflow to answer that question, covering areas like pulling

00:01:18.620 --> 00:01:21.699
data and communicating with colleagues.

00:01:21.699 --> 00:01:27.019
Because of these two factors, internal packages can add a lot of value by interfacing internal

00:01:27.019 --> 00:01:33.019
utilities, streamlining the analysis process, and empowering data scientists to create high-quality

00:01:33.019 --> 00:01:34.019
results.

00:01:34.019 --> 00:01:40.419
But, more than the tasks they can do, today I want to talk about how to design such internal

00:01:40.419 --> 00:01:44.620
packages to be as rich in context as possible.

00:01:44.620 --> 00:01:50.139
To do this, I like to think about the popular jobs-to-be-done framework for product development.

00:01:50.139 --> 00:01:54.940
This asserts that we hire a product to do a job that helps us make progress towards

00:01:54.940 --> 00:01:55.940
the goal.

00:01:55.940 --> 00:02:01.300
And, to me, it's that notion of progress, and truly knowing the ins and outs of what

00:02:01.300 --> 00:02:06.099
sort of progress our users need to make that sets internal packages apart.

00:02:06.099 --> 00:02:11.419
Additionally, these jobs can have functional, social, and emotional aspects.

00:02:11.419 --> 00:02:17.339
For the rest of this discussion, I'll tweak this framework just slightly.

00:02:17.339 --> 00:02:23.179
Let's build a team of packages to do the jobs that help our org answer impactful questions

00:02:23.179 --> 00:02:25.460
with efficient workflows.

00:02:25.460 --> 00:02:28.539
So what sort of teammates should our packages be?

00:02:28.539 --> 00:02:29.539
Let's meet a few.

00:02:29.539 --> 00:02:33.820
First, I'd like to introduce you to the IT guy.

00:02:33.820 --> 00:02:37.820
Think of a helpful or friendly IT or DevOps colleague that you may know.

00:02:37.820 --> 00:02:42.059
They're fantastic at handling the quirks of infrastructure and abstracting away all the

00:02:42.059 --> 00:02:45.899
sorts of things that data scientists don't want to spend their time thinking about, like

00:02:45.899 --> 00:02:49.940
proxies, connections, servers, etc.

00:02:49.940 --> 00:02:54.380
In that abstraction process, they also take on additional responsibilities to promote

00:02:54.380 --> 00:02:58.339
good practices like data security and credential management.

00:02:58.339 --> 00:03:03.419
Ideally, they can save us a lot of time and frustration in navigating organization-specific

00:03:03.419 --> 00:03:08.619
roadblocks that no amount of searching on Stack Overflow can help.

00:03:08.619 --> 00:03:12.220
So how can we encode these characteristics in a package?

00:03:12.220 --> 00:03:16.779
Writing utility functions can help achieve that same type of abstraction.

00:03:16.779 --> 00:03:22.500
And in these functions, we can take an opinionated stance and craft helpful error messages.

00:03:22.500 --> 00:03:24.820
Let's take a look at an example.

00:03:24.820 --> 00:03:29.339
Suppose we want to write a function to connect ourselves to a database.

00:03:29.339 --> 00:03:35.339
First, we might start out with a rather boilerplate piece of code using the DBI package.

00:03:35.339 --> 00:03:40.940
We take in the username and password, hardcode the driver name, server location, port, and

00:03:40.940 --> 00:03:43.300
return the connection object.

00:03:43.300 --> 00:03:48.500
Now let's suppose our organization has strict rules against putting secure credentials in

00:03:48.500 --> 00:03:51.300
plain text, as well they should.

00:03:51.300 --> 00:03:56.220
In an open-source package, I wouldn't presume to force users' hands to use one specific

00:03:56.220 --> 00:03:57.539
system setup.

00:03:57.539 --> 00:04:03.380
However, in this case, we can make strong assumptions based on our knowledge of an organization's

00:04:03.380 --> 00:04:05.660
rules and norms.

00:04:05.660 --> 00:04:10.779
And this sort of function can be great leverage to incentivize users to do the right thing,

00:04:10.779 --> 00:04:14.940
like storing their credentials in environment variables, because it's the only way they

00:04:14.940 --> 00:04:17.260
can get the function to work.

00:04:17.260 --> 00:04:21.619
Of course, that's only helpful if we provide descriptive error messages when the user does

00:04:21.619 --> 00:04:24.059
not have their credentials set up this way.

00:04:24.059 --> 00:04:29.059
Otherwise, they'll get an error that dbPaths is missing, find nothing useful online to

00:04:29.059 --> 00:04:33.200
help them troubleshoot, since this is an internal choice that we made.

00:04:33.200 --> 00:04:38.339
So we can enhance this function with an extremely custom and prescriptive error message explaining

00:04:38.339 --> 00:04:45.260
what went wrong, and either how to fix it, or where we can get more information.

00:04:45.260 --> 00:04:50.600
Of course, even better than explaining errors is preventing them from occurring at all.

00:04:50.600 --> 00:04:56.220
We might also know at our specific organization that non-alphanumeric characters are required

00:04:56.220 --> 00:05:01.899
in passwords, and that dbConnect doesn't natively encode these correctly when passing them to

00:05:01.899 --> 00:05:02.899
the database.

00:05:02.899 --> 00:05:07.579
Instead of troubling the user and telling them how to pick their password, we can instead

00:05:07.579 --> 00:05:10.940
handle this silently inside of the function.

00:05:10.940 --> 00:05:16.940
However, strong opinions and complete independence don't always make a great colleague.

00:05:16.940 --> 00:05:20.779
Other times, we might want someone more like a junior analyst.

00:05:20.779 --> 00:05:25.420
They know a good bit about the organization, and we can trust them to execute calculations

00:05:25.420 --> 00:05:28.859
correctly and make reasonable assumptions.

00:05:28.859 --> 00:05:33.260
At the same time, we want them to be responsive to our feedback and willing to try things

00:05:33.260 --> 00:05:35.420
out in more ways than one.

00:05:35.420 --> 00:05:39.459
So how can we capture these jobs in an internal package?

00:05:39.459 --> 00:05:45.940
We can build in proactive yet responsive functions with default arguments, reserved keywords,

00:05:45.940 --> 00:05:46.940
and the ellipsis.

00:05:46.940 --> 00:05:53.859
To illustrate, imagine a basic visualization function that wraps ggplot2 code but allows

00:05:53.859 --> 00:06:00.100
users to input their preferred x, y, and grouping variables to draw cohort groups.

00:06:00.100 --> 00:06:05.100
This function is fine, but we can probably draw on institutional knowledge to push our

00:06:05.100 --> 00:06:09.179
junior analyst to be a little bit more proactive.

00:06:09.179 --> 00:06:14.140
If we relied on the same opinionated design as the IT guy, we might consider hardcoding

00:06:14.140 --> 00:06:17.019
some of the variables inside of the function.

00:06:17.019 --> 00:06:19.899
Here though, that isn't a great approach.

00:06:19.899 --> 00:06:22.660
It isn't the junior analyst's job to give edicts.

00:06:22.660 --> 00:06:27.260
We might know what the desired x-axis will be 80% of the time, but hardcoding here is

00:06:27.260 --> 00:06:32.700
too strong of an assumption and decreases the usefulness of the function for that other

00:06:32.700 --> 00:06:33.700
20%.

00:06:33.700 --> 00:06:39.179
Instead, we can put our best guess 80% right names as the default arguments in the function

00:06:39.179 --> 00:06:43.739
header, ordered by decreasing likelihood of the need to override.

00:06:43.739 --> 00:06:47.899
This means when users do not provide their own value, a default is used.

00:06:47.899 --> 00:06:53.619
That's the junior analyst's best guess, but users retain complete control to change

00:06:53.619 --> 00:06:56.500
it as they see fit.

00:06:56.500 --> 00:07:01.179
This approach becomes even more powerful if we can abstract out a small set of incredibly

00:07:01.179 --> 00:07:07.019
common, frequently occurring, assumed variable names or other values.

00:07:07.019 --> 00:07:12.100
We can define and document this set of keywords or special variable names that span all of

00:07:12.100 --> 00:07:14.299
our internal packages.

00:07:14.299 --> 00:07:18.959
If these are well-known and well-documented, users will get into the habit of shaping their

00:07:18.959 --> 00:07:24.940
data so it plays nice with the package ecosystem and saves a lot of manual typing.

00:07:24.940 --> 00:07:29.700
This type of incentive to standardize file names can have other convenient consequences

00:07:29.700 --> 00:07:34.380
in making data extracts more shareable and code more readable.

00:07:34.380 --> 00:07:39.980
Finally, one other nice trick in making our functions responsive to feedback is the ellipsis,

00:07:39.980 --> 00:07:41.980
or passing the dots.

00:07:41.980 --> 00:07:46.260
This allows users to provide any number of arbitrary additional arguments beyond what

00:07:46.260 --> 00:07:51.899
was specified by the developer, and plugs them in at a designated place in the function

00:07:51.899 --> 00:07:52.899
body.

00:07:53.579 --> 00:07:58.700
This way, users can extend functions based on needs that the developer could not have

00:07:58.700 --> 00:08:04.299
anticipated, like customizing the color, size, and line type.

00:08:04.299 --> 00:08:10.059
So far, we've mostly focused on that first dimension, making our package teammates targeted

00:08:10.059 --> 00:08:13.820
to solving specific internal problems.

00:08:13.820 --> 00:08:16.779
But there's just as much value in that second dimension.

00:08:16.779 --> 00:08:21.940
Using internal packages as a way to ship not just calculations, but workflows, and to share

00:08:21.940 --> 00:08:25.859
an understanding of how the broader organization operates.

00:08:25.859 --> 00:08:29.500
To illustrate this, consider our intrepid tech lead.

00:08:29.500 --> 00:08:33.739
We value this type of teammate because they can draw from a breadth of past experience

00:08:33.739 --> 00:08:38.739
and institutional knowledge to help you weigh tradeoffs, learn from collected wisdom, and

00:08:38.739 --> 00:08:41.260
inspire you to do your best work.

00:08:41.260 --> 00:08:46.159
So that's a pretty tall order to put in a package, but conscientious use of vignettes

00:08:46.159 --> 00:08:50.059
and templates can help us towards this goal.

00:08:50.179 --> 00:08:55.580
Vignettes often help introduce basic functionality of a package with a toy example, as found

00:08:55.580 --> 00:08:57.380
in the declier vignette.

00:08:57.380 --> 00:09:02.460
Or less commonly, they may discuss a statistical method that's implemented, as done in the

00:09:02.460 --> 00:09:03.460
survival package.

00:09:03.460 --> 00:09:09.419
Vignettes of an internal R package can do more diverse and numerous jobs.

00:09:09.419 --> 00:09:15.140
These vignettes can accumulate the hard-won experience and domain knowledge like an experienced

00:09:15.140 --> 00:09:20.419
tech lead's photographic memory, and they hand-deliver these insights to anyone currently

00:09:20.419 --> 00:09:23.659
working on a related analysis.

00:09:23.659 --> 00:09:30.219
Just as a few examples, you can consider having completely code-free vignettes that conceptually

00:09:30.219 --> 00:09:35.179
introduce you to a common problem that your package solves, explain the workflow and key

00:09:35.179 --> 00:09:41.099
questions you should be asking yourself along the way, and even potentially get into procedural

00:09:41.099 --> 00:09:46.780
weeds like what you need to do to add features or deploy a model.

00:09:46.780 --> 00:09:51.340
Then after aligning with your users on a conceptual framework, you may introduce the package's

00:09:51.340 --> 00:09:55.059
functionality and explain how those two overlap.

00:09:55.059 --> 00:09:59.140
When your package contains functions for many different ways to do a task, you can also

00:09:59.140 --> 00:10:03.500
compare pros and cons and explain different situations where different ones have proven

00:10:03.500 --> 00:10:05.500
more or less effective.

00:10:05.500 --> 00:10:10.619
Finally, vignettes can also include lessons learned, reflections from past users, and

00:10:10.619 --> 00:10:16.380
references to past examples to help analysts learn about similar projects.

00:10:16.380 --> 00:10:21.619
In fact, all of that context may be so helpful even to people that are not direct users of

00:10:21.619 --> 00:10:25.380
your package, they may want to seek this mentorship.

00:10:25.380 --> 00:10:29.580
In this case, you can use the Packagedown package to automatically create a package

00:10:29.580 --> 00:10:34.619
website to share these vignettes with anyone who needs to learn more about a specific problem

00:10:34.619 --> 00:10:35.619
space.

00:10:35.619 --> 00:10:40.419
With a single function call, your package can share its wisdom more broadly.

00:10:40.419 --> 00:10:45.859
And, unlike their human counterparts, the package tech lead can always find time for

00:10:45.859 --> 00:10:48.140
another meeting.

00:10:48.140 --> 00:10:52.780
Similar to vignettes, embedded templates take on a more important and distinctive role for

00:10:52.780 --> 00:10:54.780
internal packages.

00:10:54.780 --> 00:11:00.219
In open-source packages, our Markdown templates provide a pre-populated file instead of the

00:11:00.219 --> 00:11:01.219
default.

00:11:01.380 --> 00:11:04.859
This is most commonly used to demonstrate proper formatting syntax.

00:11:04.859 --> 00:11:10.059
For example, the Flux Dashboard package uses a template to show users how to set up the

00:11:10.059 --> 00:11:13.780
YAML metadata and section headers.

00:11:13.780 --> 00:11:19.659
Instead, internal packages can use templates to coach users through workflows because they

00:11:19.659 --> 00:11:24.700
understand the problems users are facing and the progress they hope to achieve.

00:11:24.700 --> 00:11:29.940
Internal packages can mentor users and structure their work in two different ways.

00:11:29.940 --> 00:11:34.580
Package walkthroughs can serve as interactive notebooks that coach users through common

00:11:34.580 --> 00:11:35.580
analyses.

00:11:35.580 --> 00:11:42.020
As an example, if a type of analysis requires manual data cleaning and curation, a template

00:11:42.020 --> 00:11:46.539
notebook can guide users to ask the right questions of their data and generate common

00:11:46.539 --> 00:11:49.020
views they need to analyze.

00:11:49.020 --> 00:11:55.140
We can also include full end-to-end analysis outlines which include placeholder text, commentary,

00:11:55.140 --> 00:12:00.340
and code if the type of analysis that a package supports usually results in a specific type

00:12:00.340 --> 00:12:02.340
of report.

00:12:02.340 --> 00:12:08.979
Similarly, our package can include a project template, not just in our Markdown template.

00:12:08.979 --> 00:12:13.900
These templates can pre-define a standard file structure and a boilerplate set of files

00:12:13.900 --> 00:12:18.500
for a new project to give users a helping hand and drive the kind of consistency across

00:12:18.500 --> 00:12:23.580
projects that any tech lead dreams of when doing a code review.

00:12:23.580 --> 00:12:28.059
Speaking of collaboration, brings us to the last teammate whose traits we want our package

00:12:28.059 --> 00:12:30.979
to evoke, the project manager.

00:12:30.979 --> 00:12:36.580
One of the biggest differences between task-doing versus problem-solving packages is understanding

00:12:36.580 --> 00:12:42.140
the whole workflow and helping coordinate the project across different components.

00:12:42.140 --> 00:12:47.979
When writing open-source packages, we rightly assume that our intended audience is our users,

00:12:47.979 --> 00:12:53.179
but on a true cross-functional internal team, not everyone will be, so we can intentionally

00:12:53.179 --> 00:12:59.219
modularize the workflow and think about how to augment RStudio's IDE to make sure our

00:12:59.219 --> 00:13:03.700
tools work well with all of our colleagues.

00:13:03.700 --> 00:13:08.460
One way to do this is with modularizing the parts of the workflow that really do or do

00:13:08.460 --> 00:13:10.500
not require R code.

00:13:10.500 --> 00:13:15.900
For example, in the templates we just discussed, we could actually make separate template components

00:13:15.900 --> 00:13:22.299
for the parts that require R code and for the parts that are just English text and commentary.

00:13:22.299 --> 00:13:27.580
The commentary files can be plain vanilla markdown files that any collaborator could

00:13:27.580 --> 00:13:32.780
edit without even having to have R installed, and the main R markdown can pull in this plain

00:13:32.780 --> 00:13:36.059
text output using child documents.

00:13:36.059 --> 00:13:40.820
This approach is now made even easier with advances in the RStudio IDE.

00:13:40.820 --> 00:13:46.099
The visual markdown editor provides a great graphical user interface to support word processing

00:13:46.099 --> 00:13:51.460
in markdown for those plain text narrative documents that we just discussed.

00:13:51.460 --> 00:13:57.059
We can also use RStudio add-ins to extend the RStudio interface and ship interactive

00:13:57.059 --> 00:13:59.500
widgets in our internal packages.

00:13:59.500 --> 00:14:04.299
To illustrate, I've shown the point-and-click plot coding assistant from the open-source

00:14:04.299 --> 00:14:06.739
Esquisse package.

00:14:06.739 --> 00:14:10.340
Add-ins require more investment up front, but they're much easier to maintain than a

00:14:10.340 --> 00:14:15.020
full application, and they can help convert teammates to R users.

00:14:15.179 --> 00:14:21.940
Besides, a good project manager is willing to go that extra mile to support their team.

00:14:21.940 --> 00:14:27.020
Now speaking of collaboration, we've talked about what can make an individual package

00:14:27.020 --> 00:14:29.099
a good teammate.

00:14:29.099 --> 00:14:33.900
Another major opportunity when building a suite of internal tools is that we can think

00:14:33.900 --> 00:14:38.659
about how multiple packages on our team can best work together.

00:14:38.659 --> 00:14:44.140
We want teammates that are clear communicators, have defined responsibilities, and keep their

00:14:44.260 --> 00:14:46.820
promises.

00:14:46.820 --> 00:14:51.979
We can help packages be these sorts of good teammates with naming conventions, clearly

00:14:51.979 --> 00:14:58.659
defined scopes, and careful attention to dependencies in testing.

00:14:58.659 --> 00:15:03.340
Clear function naming conventions and consistent method signatures help packages effectively

00:15:03.340 --> 00:15:07.380
communicate with both package and human collaborators.

00:15:07.619 --> 00:15:14.299
Internally, we can give our suite of internal packages a richer language by defining a consistent

00:15:14.299 --> 00:15:20.020
set of prefixes for the namesteps that indicate how each function is to be used.

00:15:20.020 --> 00:15:24.619
One approach I like is that each function prefix can denote the type of object that

00:15:24.619 --> 00:15:26.580
that function will return.

00:15:26.580 --> 00:15:32.940
For example, using viz prefixes for functions that return ggplot2 objects.

00:15:32.940 --> 00:15:37.979
This way, past experience working with one internal package seamlessly translates to

00:15:37.979 --> 00:15:39.979
the next.

00:15:39.979 --> 00:15:45.260
Another aspect of good team communication is having clearly defined roles and responsibilities.

00:15:45.260 --> 00:15:50.460
Again, since we own our whole internal stack of packages, we have more freedom in how we

00:15:50.460 --> 00:15:56.619
can choose to divide up functionality and responsibilities across packages.

00:15:56.619 --> 00:16:02.340
Take for example the data science workflow as described in the R for Data Science book.

00:16:02.739 --> 00:16:07.299
Open-source packages inevitably have overlapping functionality, which forces users to compare

00:16:07.299 --> 00:16:10.500
alternatives and decide which is best.

00:16:10.500 --> 00:16:15.780
Internally, we can use some amount of central planning to ensure each package teammate has

00:16:15.780 --> 00:16:20.659
a clearly defined role, whether that be to provide a horizontal utility or to enable

00:16:20.659 --> 00:16:24.020
progress on a specific workstream.

00:16:24.020 --> 00:16:28.580
And just like one team ought to work well with another, that central planning can include

00:16:28.580 --> 00:16:34.020
the curation and promotion of open-source tools along with our internal ones.

00:16:34.020 --> 00:16:38.260
After all, no one team can do it all alone.

00:16:38.260 --> 00:16:43.460
When assigning these roles to our team of packages, we should consider how to manage

00:16:43.460 --> 00:16:50.020
the dependencies between them when different functionality needs to be shared across packages.

00:16:50.020 --> 00:16:54.500
Packages often have direct dependencies where a function in one package calls a function

00:16:54.500 --> 00:16:55.739
in another.

00:16:55.739 --> 00:17:00.780
This is not necessarily bad, but especially with internal packages, which might sometimes

00:17:00.780 --> 00:17:06.699
have a shorter shelf life and fewer developers, this can sometimes create a domino effect.

00:17:06.699 --> 00:17:11.819
If one package is deprecated or decides to retire or take a vacation, we don't want

00:17:11.819 --> 00:17:14.780
the rest of our ecosystem affected.

00:17:14.780 --> 00:17:20.540
Alternatively, we can use the fact that both packages A and B are under our control to

00:17:20.540 --> 00:17:25.579
see if we can eliminate the explicit dependency by promoting a clean handoff.

00:17:25.579 --> 00:17:30.619
We can see if a function in A can produce an output that B can consume instead of calling

00:17:30.619 --> 00:17:32.699
A's function directly.

00:17:32.699 --> 00:17:38.060
Additionally, because we own the full stack, we may also consider if there are shared needs

00:17:38.060 --> 00:17:45.420
in A and B that should be extracted into a common building block package C. For instance,

00:17:45.420 --> 00:17:48.660
a set of common visualization function primitives.

00:17:48.660 --> 00:17:53.859
This way, we at least have a clear hierarchy of dependencies instead of a spider web and

00:17:53.859 --> 00:17:57.780
can identify a small number of truly essential ones.

00:17:57.780 --> 00:18:02.260
Regardless of the type of dependencies we end up with, we can use tests to make sure

00:18:02.260 --> 00:18:06.979
our packages are reliable teammates who do what they promised.

00:18:06.979 --> 00:18:12.420
Typically, if I write package B that depends on package A, I can only control package B's

00:18:12.420 --> 00:18:18.900
tests, so I could write tests to see if A continues to perform as B is expecting.

00:18:18.900 --> 00:18:23.140
This is a good safeguard, but it means that we will only detect problems after they've

00:18:23.140 --> 00:18:28.180
already been introduced in A. There's nothing in place to actually stop package A from getting

00:18:28.180 --> 00:18:30.660
distracted in the first place.

00:18:30.660 --> 00:18:37.540
Instead, we prefer that both A and B be conscientious of the promises they've made and stay committed

00:18:37.540 --> 00:18:40.500
to working towards their shared goal.

00:18:40.500 --> 00:18:43.979
We can formalize that shared vision with integration tests.

00:18:43.979 --> 00:18:49.020
That is, we can add tests to both the upstream and the downstream packages to ensure they

00:18:49.099 --> 00:18:53.420
continue to check in with each other and inquire if any of the changes they're planning could

00:18:53.420 --> 00:18:54.420
be disruptive.

00:18:54.420 --> 00:18:59.660
Now, just imagine having such rigorous and ongoing communication and prioritization with

00:18:59.660 --> 00:19:02.180
your own teammates.

00:19:02.180 --> 00:19:06.339
In summary, we all know the joy of working with a great team.

00:19:06.339 --> 00:19:10.420
And given that you're here right now, I suspect you know the pleasure of cracking

00:19:10.420 --> 00:19:12.420
open a new R package.

00:19:12.420 --> 00:19:17.459
By taking advantage of the unique opportunities of designing internal packages, we can achieve

00:19:17.459 --> 00:19:19.459
the best of both worlds.

00:19:19.459 --> 00:19:24.099
We can share the fun of working with good tools with the teammates we care about.

00:19:24.099 --> 00:19:29.339
And we can elevate those tools to full-fledged teammates by giving them the skills they need

00:19:29.339 --> 00:19:30.339
to succeed.

00:19:30.339 --> 00:19:31.219
Thank you.

